    1021 var bc = 0, bs, buffer, idx = 0, output = '';

    1025 ~buffer && (bs = bc % 4 ? bs * 64 + buffer : buffer,

    482 /** 589
    483 * Builds the token request options. Does not make the request, just

    485 */ 592
    486 function buildTokenRequest(env, code, state) { 593
    487 10 const { redirectUri, clientSecret, tokenUri, clientId, pkce } = state; 595
    488 10 if (!redirectUri) { 597
    489 1 throw new Error("Missing state.redirectUri"); 598
    490 } 599
    491 9 if (!tokenUri) { 601
    492 1 throw new Error("Missing state.tokenUri"); 602
    493 } 603
    494 8 if (!clientId) { 605
    495 1 throw new Error("Missing state.clientId"); 606

    497 7 const requestOptions = { 609
    498 method: "POST", 610
    499 headers: { "content-type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded" }, 611
    500 body: `code=${code}&grant_type=authorization_code&redirect_uri=${encodeURIComponent(redirectUri)}` 613
    501 }; 614
    502 // For public apps, authentication is not possible (and thus not required), 616
    503 // since a client with no secret cannot prove its identity when it issues a 617
    504 // call. (The end-to-end system can still be secure because the client comes 618
    505 // from a known, https protected endpoint specified and enforced by the 619
    506 // redirect uri.) For confidential apps, an Authorization header using HTTP 620
    507 // Basic authentication is required, where the username is the app’s 621
    508 // client_id and the password is the app’s client_secret (see example). 622
    509

    clientSecret
    ) {
    		 623

    512 } 628

    518 1 requestOptions.body += `&code_verifier=${(pkce.code_verifier)}`; 633
    519 } 634
    520 } 635

    540 /** 657
    541 * This function can be used when you want to handle everything in one page
    542 * (no launch endpoint needed). You can think of it as if it does:
    543 * ```js
    544 * authorize(options).then(ready)
    545 * ```
    546 *
    547 * **Be careful with init()!** There are some details you need to be aware of:
    548 *
    549 * 1. It will only work if your launch_uri is the same as your redirect_uri.
    550 * While this should be valid, we can’t promise that every EHR will allow you
    551 * to register client with such settings.
    552 * 2. Internally, `init()` will be called twice. First it will redirect to the
    553 * EHR, then the EHR will redirect back to the page where init() will be
    554 * called again to complete the authorization. This is generally fine,
    555 * because the returned promise will only be resolved once, after the second
    556 * execution, but please also consider the following:
    557 * - You should wrap all your app’s code in a function that is only executed
    558 * after `init()` resolves!
    559 * - Since the page will be loaded twice, you must be careful if your code
    560 * has global side effects that can persist between page reloads
    561 * (for example writing to localStorage).
    562 * 3. For standalone launch, only use init in combination with offline_access
    563 * scope. Once the access_token expires, if you don’t have a refresh_token
    564 * there is no way to re-authorize properly. We detect that and delete the
    565 * expired access token, but it still means that the user will have to
    566 * refresh the page twice to re-authorize.
    567 * @param env The adapter
    568 * @param options The authorize options
    569 */ 686
    570 async function init(env, options) { 687
    571 6 const url = env.getUrl(); 689
    572 6 const code = url.searchParams.get("code"); 690
    573 6 const state = url.searchParams.get("state"); 691
    574 // if `code` and `state` params are present we need to complete the auth flow 693
    575 6 if (code && state) { 694
    576 2 return completeAuth(env); 695
    577 } 696
    578 // Check for existing client state. If state is found, it means a client 698
    579 // instance have already been created in this session and we should try to 699
    580 // "revive" it. 700
    581 4 const storage = env.getStorage(); 701
    582 4 const key = state || await storage.get(settings_1.SMART_KEY); 702
    583 4 const cached = await storage.get(key); 703
    584 4 if (cached) { 704
    585 2 return new Client_1.default(env, cached); 705
    586 } 706
    587 // Otherwise try to launch 708
    588 2 return authorize(env, options).then(() => { 709
    589 // `init` promises a Client but that cannot happen in this case. The 710
    590 // browser will be redirected (unload the page and be redirected back 711
    591 // to it later and the same init function will be called again). On 712
    592 // success, authorize will resolve with the redirect url but we don't 713
    593 // want to return that from this promise chain because it is not a 714
    594 // Client instance. At the same time, if authorize fails, we do want to 715
    595 // pass the error to those waiting for a client instance. 716
    596 return new Promise(() => { }); 717
    597 }); 718
    598 } 719
